"""
mkt-context | 1 Kings | chapters 15–17 (fill)
run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1kings-15-17-fill.py

Covers all missing verses in chs 15–17 (88 missing; 4 already present).
Key decisions:
- Ch15: Regnal formulas, the gĕbîrāh institution, Asa's reform, Aram-Damascus treaty
- Ch16: Omri's Samaria (archaeologically attested), Ahab-Jezebel Phoenician alliance,
        Omri-dynasty in Assyrian records as "house of Omri"
- Ch17: Elijah's Tishbite origins, Zarephath/Sarepta archaeological context,
        ancient Near Eastern parallels to prophetic life-restoration accounts
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        existing.setdefault(ch, {})
        for v, html in verses.items():
            existing[ch].setdefault(v, html)

KINGS = {
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>The regnal formula for Abijam (= Abijah in Chronicles) synchronizes his accession: 'In the eighteenth year of King Jeroboam son of Nebat, Abijam began to reign over Judah.' The synchronistic regnal formula — giving the accession year of the southern king relative to the reigning northern king — is characteristic of the Deuteronomistic History's chronological framework. The system depends on two independent year-counting traditions (Judahite and Israelite) that differ in when the new year begins and how accession years are counted, explaining apparent discrepancies in modern calculations of biblical chronology.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Abijam's regnal summary: three years in Jerusalem. His mother is identified as Maacah daughter of Abishalom — the same Maacah who will appear in v13 as queen mother (<em>gᵉḇîrāh</em>). The identification of the king's mother is standard in Kings' evaluative formulas; the queen mother was a significant political office in Judah, with a formal title and institutional role (see on v13). Abishalom is likely a variant spelling of Absalom (cf. 2 Chr 11:20-21), making Maacah David's great-granddaughter through Absalom.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The evaluation: Abijam walked in all the sins of his father. The Deuteronomistic evaluative formula uses the verb <em>hālak</em> (walk) to describe covenant faithfulness or apostasy — walking in YHWH's ways or in the ways of apostate predecessors. Abijam's heart (<em>lēḇāḇ</em>) was not wholly devoted to YHWH his God — the wholeness formula (<em>šālēm</em>, complete, undivided) is the standard of the Deuteronomistic evaluation; David's divided <em>not</em>-wholeness remains the paradox that the narrator resolves by invoking the Davidic covenant.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The exception clause: 'Yet for David's sake the LORD his God gave him a lamp in Jerusalem, raising up his son after him and establishing Jerusalem.' The <em>nîr</em> (lamp/lamp-wick) for David — preserving the Davidic line despite Abijam's failure — is the covenant-preservation motif that runs through Kings. The 'lamp' metaphor appears also in 2 Sam 21:17 ('you shall not go out with us to battle, lest you quench the lamp of Israel'); the continuity of the Davidic house is the lamp that YHWH tends despite individual kings' failures.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Davidic exception: David did what was right in YHWH's eyes and did not turn aside from anything he commanded him all the days of his life, except in the matter of Uriah the Hittite. The parenthetical exception — the Bathsheba-Uriah affair of 2 Sam 11-12 — is the one recorded blot on David's record, acknowledged rather than suppressed. This honest narrative accounting contrasts with ancient royal annals that typically omit royal failures. The exception clause's presence underscores that the evaluation of David is historical, not hagiographic.</p>",
    "6": "<p>War between Rehoboam and Jeroboam continued all the days of Abijam's life — or, in some manuscripts, 'all the days of his life [Abijam's].' The textual note reflects a variation between MT and some manuscripts. The persistent state of border conflict between Judah and Israel — rather than decisive battle — characterizes the early divided monarchy period. The border zone between the two kingdoms in Benjamin (cf. ch15 vv17-22) was the site of intermittent military pressure rather than open war.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The source citation: 'Are not the acts of Abijam... written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Judah?' The <em>sēper diḇrê hayyāmîm lᵉmalkê yᵉhûḏāh</em> (Book of the Words/Chronicles of the Days of the Kings of Judah) is one of the Deuteronomistic Historian's principal sources, cited 15 times for Judahite kings. This is a distinct document from the canonical 1–2 Chronicles; it was a court record or official annals that the historian had access to but which has not survived independently.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Abijam died and was buried in the city of David — the traditional Davidic tomb-complex on the southeastern ridge of Jerusalem. The burial formula ('slept with his fathers' + burial location) is the standard closing formula for Judahite kings who died in office. The David tomb-city as the burial site for all Judahite kings before Hezekiah signals the continuity of the Davidic dynasty and its territorial identification with the original city of David.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Asa's accession synchronization: 'In the twentieth year of Jeroboam king of Israel, Asa began to reign over Judah.' Asa's reign of 41 years (v10) makes him one of the longer-reigning Judahite kings. His reign overlaps substantially with those of Baasha (16:6-7) and the beginning of the Omride dynasty in the north. The 41-year reign is remarkable: Asa would have been a child at accession (his mother Maacah is still the queen mother from Abijam's reign, suggesting Asa came to the throne young).</p>",
    "10": "<p>Asa's mother is also named Maacah daughter of Abishalom — the same person as Abijam's mother, meaning Asa's mother and grandmother are the same woman, or (more likely) that Maacah is Asa's grandmother who continues as <em>gᵉḇîrāh</em>. The retention of the queen mother position across two reigns is attested in other ancient Near Eastern courts; the office did not automatically transfer to the new king's biological mother but could be held by a senior woman of the royal household.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The positive Deuteronomistic evaluation: 'Asa did what was right in the eyes of YHWH as David his father had done.' Only a handful of Judahite kings receive this unqualified positive assessment: Asa, Jehoshaphat, Hezekiah, and Josiah. The comparison to David remains the benchmark. The Hebrew <em>kᵉdāwid ʾāḇîhû</em> (as David his father) treats David as the paradigm king against whom all successors are measured — the standard established at 2 Sam 7 is the measuring rod of Kings.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Asa's reform program: he removed the male cult prostitutes (<em>qᵉḏēšîm</em>) from the land and removed all the idols (<em>gillûlîm</em>) that his fathers had made. The <em>qᵉḏēšîm</em> (singular <em>qāḏēš</em>) are sacred functionaries associated with Canaanite religious practice; the exact nature of their role is debated, with 'cult prostitute' a traditional translation and 'sacred functionary' or 'devotee' as alternatives. Their presence alongside <em>gillûlîm</em> (a contemptuous term for idols, from <em>gillāh</em>, dung-pellet) identifies the Canaanite religious infrastructure that has penetrated Judah since Rehoboam.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Queen mother Maacah deposed for the Asherah: see v10 note. The <em>gᵉḇîrāh</em> institution — the formal queen-mother role — is attested at Ugarit and in Neo-Assyrian contexts; it involved real political influence and, apparently, religious responsibilities. Maacah had made an <em>mipleṣet</em> for the Asherah — the term <em>mipleṣet</em> (something horrifying, a monstrous cult image) is unique to this passage and its parallel (2 Chr 15:16). The Asherah pole/tree/image as a cult object associated with Canaanite female deity worship is attested in Ugaritic texts and in Israelite inscriptions from Kuntillet Ajrud that refer to 'YHWH and his Asherah.'</p>",
    "14": "<p>The qualifying note: the high places were not removed, though Asa's heart was wholly true to YHWH all his days. The tension between the Deuteronomistic ideal (all worship centralized in Jerusalem) and the persistent reality of local high places (<em>bāmôt</em>) recurs throughout Kings. Even reforming kings who receive positive evaluations fail to abolish the high places. Only Hezekiah (2 Kgs 18:4) and Josiah (2 Kgs 23:8) are credited with removing them. The heart-wholeness formula here contrasts with Abijam's divided heart (v3).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Asa brought into the house of YHWH the sacred gifts his father had dedicated and his own sacred gifts — silver, gold, and vessels. The practice of dedicating captured or tributary precious metals to the temple treasury is attested throughout the ancient Near East; temple treasuries functioned as both sacred deposits and state reserves. Asa's act of bringing his father's dedicatory gifts reverses the pattern of temple-plundering (as under Shishak, 1 Kgs 14:26) — filling rather than emptying the treasury.</p>",
    "16": "<p>War between Asa and Baasha of Israel all their days. Baasha's reign (15:33) begins in Asa's third year; the border conflict between them centers on the Benjamin territory between the two kingdoms. The political geography of the divided monarchy placed the border approximately at Mizpah and Ramah — towns in Benjamin that Benjamin's traditional territory shared between the two kingdoms, making this zone perpetually contested.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Baasha built Ramah — possibly Tell er-Ram, about 8 km north of Jerusalem — to prevent anyone from going out or coming in to Asa king of Judah. Ramah's fortification as a border fort controlling the main north-south road through Benjamin was a strategic move to block communications between Judah and the northern territories. The tactic of controlling road-towns to restrict movement is a classic ANE military strategy; the Assyrians used similar fortified road-posts to control subject territories.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Asa took all the silver and gold remaining in the treasuries of the house of YHWH and the house of the king and sent them to Ben-hadad son of Tabrimmon son of Hezion king of Aram-Damascus. The three-generation genealogy of Ben-hadad establishes this as Ben-hadad I, the founder of the Aramean dynasty at Damascus. The name Ben-hadad (<em>bar-hadad</em>, son of Hadad) is a dynastic throne-name; the historical Ben-hadad I is attested in the Melqart Stele (found 1940 near Aleppo), which mentions his father Tabrimmon. The temple treasury as state financial reserve — available for tributary payments — is consistent with ancient Near Eastern practice.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The treaty proposal: 'There is a covenant between me and you, between my father and your father' — invoking a previous treaty relationship. The <em>bᵉrît</em> (covenant/treaty) between Judah and Aram was a diplomatic alliance needing renewal. Asa's request that Ben-hadad break his treaty (<em>bᵉrît</em>) with Baasha and align with Judah instead is a classic piece of ancient Near Eastern diplomacy: buying an alliance by invoking prior treaty bonds and offering fresh tribute.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Ben-hadad sends his armies against the northern cities: Ijon, Dan, Abel-maim, and all Naphtali. The list of northern territories targeted by the Aramean invasion matches the later Assyrian list of northern territories captured — Dan and Abel-maim (Abel-beth-maacah) appear in both. The Aramaean campaign effectively opened a northern front, forcing Baasha to abandon his fortification project at Ramah and withdraw to Tirzah (his capital, v21).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Baasha abandoned Ramah and lived in Tirzah. Tirzah (<em>ṯirsāh</em>) — the northern capital identified with Tell el-Farah (North), excavated by Roland de Vaux — was the seat of the northern monarchy from Jeroboam through Omri. Its name means 'pleasing, beautiful' (Cant 6:4 uses it as a byword for beauty). The abandonment of the Ramah fortification allowed Asa to exploit the situation immediately.</p>",
    "22": "<p>King Asa proclaimed a levy on all Judah — no one exempt — to carry away the stones and timber of Ramah. The <em>mas</em> (forced labor levy) was typically organized by the royal administration for public building projects (Solomon used it for the temple and his palace complex). Asa's rapid reuse of Baasha's building materials at Geba and Mizpah shows both the urgency of the response and the pragmatic reuse of worked stone — common in the ancient Near East, where quarrying and dressing stone was labor-intensive.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Asa's reign summary mentions his building projects and his power, but closes with a note about his foot disease in his old age. The Chronicler adds detail (2 Chr 16:12) that Asa sought physicians rather than YHWH for his disease — a theological evaluation of his final years. The foot disease (<em>regel</em>, lit. 'foot/leg') is unspecified medically; the phrase 'his disease was severe' (<em>kî ḥālāh lᵉḥŏlî</em>) indicates its seriousness.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Asa died and was buried in the city of David. The burial formula marks the end of his 41-year reign. The Chronicler's parallel (2 Chr 16:14) adds that they made a very great fire in his honor, laid him on a bier filled with spices and various blended preparations, and burned incense for him — suggesting a royal funeral with spice-burning honors, attested in Neo-Babylonian funeral texts as a mark of royal honor for the deceased.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Nadab son of Jeroboam accession formula: 'In the second year of Asa king of Judah, Nadab son of Jeroboam began to reign over Israel and reigned two years.' The synchronization with Asa's second year places Nadab's brief reign very early in Asa's long reign. Nadab is the only son of Jeroboam to reign; the Ahijah prophecy (1 Kgs 14:10) predicted the destruction of Jeroboam's house, and Nadab's reign and death accomplish it.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Nadab's negative evaluation: he did evil in YHWH's eyes and walked in the way of his father and in the sin by which he made Israel sin. The <em>ḥaṭṭāʾt yārāḇʿām</em> (sin of Jeroboam) formula — first applied here to a successor king — will become the standard evaluative phrase for all northern kings. The formula references Jeroboam's golden calves at Bethel and Dan (1 Kgs 12:28-30) as the definitional apostasy of the northern kingdom.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Baasha son of Ahijah of the house of Issachar conspired against Nadab and struck him at Gibbethon. Gibbethon (<em>gibbᵉṯôn</em>) — a Danite city in the Shephelah controlled by the Philistines at this period (cf. 1 Kgs 16:15-17 where Gibbethon siege recurs) — was apparently the site of an Israelite siege operation where the army was concentrated, providing the opportunity for Baasha's military coup. The pattern of military commanders using sieges as the occasion for coups recurs in Israelite history.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Baasha killed Nadab in the third year of Asa king of Judah and reigned in his place. The brief, stark formula for regicide — 'and he struck him and killed him' — becomes a pattern in the north (cf. Zimri, Shallum, Pekah). The northern monarchy's political instability contrasts with the unbroken Davidic succession in the south: in the same period Judah has one dynasty, the north cycles through multiple dynasties.</p>",
    "29": "<p>As soon as Baasha was king he struck down all the house of Jeroboam. The dynastic elimination — fulfilling Ahijah's oracle (1 Kgs 14:10) — is the standard ancient Near Eastern practice for a new dynasty consolidating power: eliminating rival claimants to prevent future challenges. The phrase 'he did not leave to Jeroboam any who breathed' echoes the <em>ḥērem</em> language of holy war applied to a royal house.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The theological interpretation: because of the sins of Jeroboam which he sinned and which he made Israel sin, and because of the anger with which he provoked YHWH the God of Israel to anger. The Deuteronomistic pattern of connecting dynastic punishment to prior sin: Jeroboam's sin produces the oracle; the oracle produces the judgment; the judgment is accomplished through a human agent (Baasha) who is himself then judged for the violence (v29: 'according to the word of YHWH which he spoke by his servant Ahijah').</p>",
    "31": "<p>The source formula: 'Are not the acts of Nadab... written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel?' The parallel source for the northern kingdom — the <em>sēper diḇrê hayyāmîm lᵉmalkê yiśrāʾēl</em> (Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel) — is cited 17 times for northern kings. Like its Judahite counterpart, this was an official court record not otherwise surviving but used by the Deuteronomistic Historian.</p>",
    "32": "<p>War between Asa and Baasha king of Israel all their days. The formula links the northern and southern narratives: the same border conflict described from Judah's perspective (vv16-22) is noted here at the close of Nadab's entry as the ongoing political reality. The Baasha narrative proper begins at v33; this verse provides the political backdrop for understanding why the Ben-hadad alliance (v18-20) was so significant.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Baasha's accession formula: 'In the third year of Asa king of Judah, Baasha son of Ahijah began to reign over all Israel in Tirzah, and reigned twenty-four years.' Tirzah as capital: Baasha inherits and maintains the previous northern capital. His 24-year reign gives the north political stability under his dynasty (supplemented by his son Elah's 2-year reign), though the Deuteronomistic evaluation (v34) groups him with Jeroboam's sin. Baasha has the longest reign of any northern king between Jeroboam I and Ahab.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Baasha's negative evaluation using the full <em>ḥaṭṭāʾt yārāḇʿām</em> formula. The irony is explicit: Baasha was YHWH's instrument to destroy Jeroboam's house (v29: 'according to the word of YHWH'), yet Baasha himself walks in the sin of Jeroboam. The judgment oracle against Baasha (ch16:1-4) uses identical language to the oracle against Jeroboam (1 Kgs 14:10-11) — dynastic repetition showing the pattern of sin, oracle, judgment recurring throughout the northern monarchy.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>The prophetic oracle frame: the word of YHWH came to Jehu son of Hanani against Baasha. Jehu son of Hanani is the northern prophet who will later confront Jehoshaphat (2 Chr 19:2) and whose father Hanani rebuked Asa for trusting Aram (2 Chr 16:7). The introduction of a prophetic oracle against Baasha parallels the Ahijah oracle against Jeroboam (ch14:7-11) — the same narrative pattern repeating: king sins, prophet pronounces judgment, dynasty ends violently. The Deuteronomistic Historian emphasizes the prophetic word as the interpretive key to dynastic history.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The oracle content: 'I exalted you from the dust and made you leader over my people Israel, and you walked in the way of Jeroboam.' The elevation from obscurity (<em>min-hāʿāp̄ār</em>, from the dust) echoes Hannah's song (1 Sam 2:8) and the general Deuteronomistic theme of YHWH raising up and bringing down kings (Deut 32:39; 1 Sam 2:6-7). The charge of walking in Jeroboam's way — making Israel sin — is the judicial ground of the coming judgment; Baasha instrumentalized as YHWH's agent against Jeroboam and then himself became the same sin he was used to punish.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The judgment formula: 'Behold, I will utterly sweep away Baasha and his house.' The verb <em>biʿartî</em> (I will sweep away) is the technical term for the complete removal of an apostate dynasty — 'I will sweep you away as one sweeps away dung' (<em>bāʿar</em>). The same verb is used in the Jeroboam oracle (1 Kgs 14:10) and will be used against Ahab's house (1 Kgs 21:21). The repetition of the sweeping-away formula creates the structural rhythm of the northern monarchy's dynastic collapses.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The curse formula: 'Anyone belonging to Baasha who dies in the city the dogs shall eat, and anyone of his who dies in the field the birds of the heavens shall eat.' This is the identical formula from the Jeroboam oracle (1 Kgs 14:11) — the denial of burial and the consumption by scavengers as the ultimate dishonor in the ANE worldview. Proper burial was a fundamental obligation of family and state; to be left for dogs and birds was the most severe public disgrace, applied to enemies in Assyrian royal inscriptions as well.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The source formula: 'Are not the acts of Baasha... written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel?' The citation closes Baasha's narrative before the dynastic judgment is narrated. The brevity of this source citation — with nothing specified about Baasha's acts of power or building — is itself evaluative: Kings records very little of a king who built for 24 years beyond his sin and its consequences.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Baasha died and was buried in Tirzah; Elah his son reigned in his place. The burial formula: Baasha receives a normal burial (ironic given the curse of vv3-4, which falls on Elah's descendants and the dynasty's survivors — see v11). The succession of Elah is the last Baasha-dynasty succession; the dynasty ends with Elah's assassination (v9-10).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The narrator's retrospective: the word of YHWH came against Baasha and against his house through the prophet Jehu son of Hanani, for all the evil that he did in the sight of YHWH. The phrase 'and also because he struck it' is interpretive — Baasha destroyed Jeroboam's house but himself became Jeroboam. The Deuteronomistic logic: judgment for sin is itself no ground for pride; the instrument of judgment is also judged for its own sins.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Elah's accession: 'In the twenty-sixth year of Asa king of Judah, Elah son of Baasha began to reign over Israel in Tirzah, and reigned two years.' The 2-year reign makes Elah one of the shorter-reigning northern kings (only Zimri's 7 days is shorter). His reign is entirely unremarkable except for his assassination; the narrative provides no positive characterization. The brevity of evaluation ('he did evil in the sight of YHWH' implied but not even explicitly stated before his death) leaves Elah as a narrative placeholder between dynasties.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Zimri's conspiracy: 'Zimri, the commander of half his chariots, conspired against him.' Zimri is a military officer — commander of half the chariot force — who exploits an opportunity when Elah is drunk at the house of Arza, the steward of the palace in Tirzah. The drunkenness (<em>šōṯeh šikkor</em>) as the condition enabling assassination appears elsewhere in ancient contexts (Holofernes drunk when Judith beheads him, Jdt 13:2); here it signals the moral condition of the king and the dynasty's end.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Zimri killed Elah and reigned in his place in the twenty-seventh year of Asa king of Judah. The terseness of the killing narrative — 'Zimri came in and struck him and killed him' — is characteristic of Kings' laconic treatment of northern coups. The theological point is the fulfillment of the Jehu oracle: the hand raised against Baasha's house is the instrument of divine judgment, however violent.</p>",
    "11": "<p>As soon as Zimri sat on his throne he killed all the house of Baasha — he did not leave him a single male of his relatives or his friends. The dynastic elimination uses the same formula as Baasha's elimination of Jeroboam's house (15:29). The formula 'he did not leave him a single one who urinates against a wall' is an idiom for any male (cf. 1 Sam 25:22, 34; 1 Kgs 21:21) — the elimination is total. The elimination is explicitly said to fulfill the Jehu oracle (v12).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Zimri destroyed all the house of Baasha according to the word of YHWH which he spoke against Baasha through the prophet Jehu — the second fulfillment notice in this chapter's narrative (the first implicit in v7). The pattern: prophetic oracle → dynastic sin → dynastic elimination. The Deuteronomistic Historian emphasizes the fulfillment of the prophetic word as evidence that YHWH controls the chaos of northern political history.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The theological summary: for all the sins of Baasha and the sins of Elah his son, which they sinned and which they made Israel sin, provoking YHWH the God of Israel to anger with their idols. The <em>haḇlîhēm</em> (their worthless idols, from <em>heḇel</em>, vapor/vanity) is a contemptuous term for idols derived from the root for breath or vapor — the same word Ecclesiastes uses for all that is transient. The <em>Jeroboam sin</em> formula reaches its logical end: the dynasty that perpetuated Jeroboam's sin is consumed by the same pattern.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Source citation for Elah's brief reign: the characteristic formula closes the narrative even though there is almost nothing to report beyond the assassination. The source citation functions as a literary closure even when the actual acts of power were negligible.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Zimri's 7-day reign: 'In the twenty-seventh year of Asa king of Judah, Zimri reigned seven days in Tirzah.' The 7-day reign is the shortest in Kings — never long enough to receive a proper regnal formula in the Deuteronomistic style. The army was besieging Gibbethon of the Philistines — the same siege ongoing since Nadab's time (15:27) — when they heard that Zimri had struck down the king.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The army made Omri the commander of the army king over Israel in the camp. The military election of a king — the army acclaiming their general as king in the field — is a practice attested in the ancient Near East. The Macedonian and later Roman parallel (soldiers proclaiming generals as emperor) shows the cross-cultural pattern. Omri is elected because the army in the field heard the coup news and needed leadership immediately; legitimacy is conferred by military power, not dynastic right.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Omri went up from Gibbethon and all Israel with him and they besieged Tirzah. The siege of the capital by the legitimate army — directed against the usurper Zimri — is a civil-war scenario compressed into a single verse. The move from the Philistine front to the internal civil war shows the political instability of the northern kingdom: the army must disengage from an external enemy to settle an internal coup.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Zimri burned the king's palace over himself and died — suicide by burning the palace down with himself inside. The phrase <em>wayyiśrop̄ ʿālāyw ʾeṯ bêṯ hammelek bāʾēš</em> describes Zimri's self-immolation rather than capture. Ancient parallels to palace burning as the last act of a defeated ruler exist in Near Eastern texts; the act is simultaneously defiant (denying the enemy the palace intact) and suicidal. The 7-day reign ends in fire.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Theological evaluation of Zimri: he sinned, doing evil in the eyes of YHWH, walking in the way of Jeroboam and his sin. The evaluation is applied even to the 7-day reign — every northern king, however briefly, is measured against the Jeroboam standard. The <em>ḥaṭṭāʾt yārāḇʿām</em> formula's application to Zimri (who had no time to do anything) indicates the Deuteronomistic Historian's theological assessment rather than a historical account of specific actions during 7 days.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Source citation for Zimri: 'Are not the acts of Zimri... written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel?' The citation formula applied even to a 7-day reign shows the consistency of the Deuteronomistic source apparatus; even marginal kings have their records in the official annals.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The division of Israel after Zimri: half followed Tibni son of Ginath to make him king, half followed Omri. The civil war between Tibni and Omri — lasting apparently 4 years until Tibni's death (v22) — shows that the military election of Omri was contested. Tibni's origins and supporters are not specified; he represents a civilian/political alternative to the military's candidate Omri. The divided kingdom of north and south now has an additionally divided north.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Omri prevailed over the followers of Tibni son of Ginath and Tibni died and Omri became king. The resolution of the Tibni-Omri conflict in Omri's favor is reported without explanation of Tibni's death — natural causes, execution, or battle are all possible. The formula 'Tibni died' leaves open the manner. The Omride dynasty begins: a dynasty that, despite its short duration (4 kings), left the most lasting mark on Israelite history and archaeology.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Omri's accession formula: 'In the thirty-first year of Asa king of Judah, Omri began to reign over Israel and reigned twelve years; he reigned six years in Tirzah.' The 12-year total reign includes the 4 years of civil conflict; the 6 years in Tirzah (before moving to Samaria) is the stable period of his reign from the Tirzah capital before founding his new capital (v24).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Omri's negative evaluation — and its escalation: 'Omri did evil in the eyes of YHWH and did more evil than all who were before him.' The escalation formula (more evil than predecessors) appears here for the first time applied to a northern king — it will be used again for Ahab (v30) and will be further escalated through the Ahab narrative. The historical Omri is known from Assyrian, Moabite, and Aramean sources as a powerful monarch; the Mesha Stele credits him with oppressing Moab for 40 years. But Kings evaluates him solely on religious grounds.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Omri walked in all the way of Jeroboam the son of Nebat and in the sins that he made Israel sin, to provoke YHWH the God of Israel to anger with their idols. The full Jeroboam formula applied to Omri. Despite the Assyrian designation of Israel as <em>bît ḥumri</em> (house of Omri) for over a century after his dynasty ended, Kings provides only this religious assessment. The Mesha Stele (Moabite Stone, c. 840 BCE) independently confirms that Omri 'oppressed Moab many days' — consistent with Assyrian records of his power, but invisible in Kings' theological account.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Source formula for Omri: 'Are not the acts of Omri... and the might that he showed, written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel?' The phrase 'the might that he showed' (<em>gᵉḇûrātô ʾăšer ʿāśāh</em>) is unusual — Kings rarely credits northern kings with <em>gᵉḇûrāh</em> (might, valor). The source citation acknowledges that the official annals recorded Omri's military and political achievements, even though Kings presents almost none of them beyond the Samaria purchase.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Omri died and was buried in Samaria — the first king buried in the city he founded. The burial in Samaria rather than Tirzah (the previous capital) marks the completion of the transition to the new capital. Ahab his son reigned in his place, initiating the most notorious reign in the northern monarchy's history.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Ahab's accession: 'In the thirty-eighth year of Asa king of Judah, Ahab son of Omri began to reign over Israel in Samaria, and Ahab the son of Omri reigned over Israel twenty-two years.' The 22-year reign is the longest in the northern monarchy. Ahab appears in Assyrian records as a participant in the anti-Assyrian coalition at the Battle of Qarqar (853 BCE), where Shalmaneser III's inscription credits him with 2,000 chariots and 10,000 soldiers — if accurate, these numbers reflect the Omride military capacity, the largest chariot force in the coalition.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Ahab's double-superlative evaluation: 'Ahab son of Omri did evil in the sight of YHWH more than all who were before him.' The escalation from Omri ('more evil than all before him,' v25) to Ahab ('more evil than all before him') shows the Deuteronomistic Historian stacking the evaluative formula in a crescendo that will be resolved only at the death of the Ahab dynasty. The Elijah narratives (chs 17-21) and the Ahab-Jezebel confrontation explain the theological basis for this extreme evaluation.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Ahab married Jezebel daughter of Ittobaal king of the Sidonians and went and served Baal and worshiped him. The marriage alliance with Phoenicia was politically advantageous — Phoenician trade contacts and Mediterranean commerce — but religiously catastrophic. Ittobaal (Ethbaal in Josephus) is independently attested in Phoenician tradition as a king of Tyre and Sidon; Josephus (<em>Contra Apion</em> 1.18) gives his name and identifies him as the father of the woman who became Ahab's wife. Jezebel's active promotion of Baal worship — as opposed to the passive tolerance of other northern kings — is what elevates Ahab's reign to the superlative.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Ahab erected an altar for Baal in the house of Baal that he built in Samaria. The building of a Baal temple in Samaria — the capital — is the institutional escalation beyond the high-place worship of previous kings. The Baal worship Jezebel imports is specifically Baal of Tyre (<em>baʿal ṣôr</em>), the chief deity of the Phoenician cities. Archaeological evidence for Baal worship in 9th-century Israel includes inscribed ivories from Samaria and cult objects.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Ahab made an Asherah pole — the installation of the Asherah symbol (pole or stylized tree) in association with the Baal temple creates the full Canaanite deity-pair: Baal and Asherah. Asherah was the consort of El in Ugaritic mythology; in Israelite syncretism she appears alongside YHWH (the Kuntillet Ajrud inscription reading 'YHWH and his Asherah' is the most famous example). The narrator's summary: 'Ahab did more to provoke the LORD the God of Israel to anger than all the kings of Israel who were before him.'</p>",
    "34": "<p>In Ahab's days Hiel of Bethel rebuilt Jericho. He laid its foundation at the cost of Abiram his firstborn, and set up its gates at the cost of his youngest son Segub, according to the word of the LORD which he spoke by Joshua son of Nun. The reference fulfills Joshua's curse (Josh 6:26): 'Cursed before YHWH be the man who rises up and rebuilds this city Jericho. At the cost of his firstborn shall he lay its foundation, and at the cost of his youngest son shall he set up its gates.' The precise fulfillment — foundation death of firstborn, gate-setting death of youngest — frames the Ahab-Elijah narrative section with a reminder that YHWH's word spoken centuries earlier operates exactly as spoken.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "2": "<p>The word of YHWH to Elijah: 'Depart from here and turn eastward and hide yourself by the brook Cherith, which is east of the Jordan.' The brook Cherith (<em>naḥal kᵉrît</em>) is not identified with certainty; the traditional location is Wadi Yabis in Transjordan, east of the Jordan. The command to hide (<em>hissātēr</em>) suggests that Elijah's safety after announcing the drought requires concealment from Ahab's court, which will search for him (18:10: 'Ahab has sent to seek you in every nation and kingdom').</p>",
    "3": "<p>The divine provision at Cherith: 'I have commanded the ravens to feed you there.' The verb <em>ṣiwwîtî</em> (I have commanded) is applied to the ravens — YHWH's sovereignty extends to directing wild birds. The LXX translators faced a problem with <em>ʿōrᵉḇîm</em>: the Hebrew is identical to the word for 'ravens' and also to the gentilc 'Arabians.' The LXX reads 'ravens' (<em>korakes</em>), following the MT. The miraculous feeding of the prophet by birds reverses the general pattern of Elijah announcing famine: the prophet himself is fed supernaturally while the land goes without rain.</p>",
    "4": "<p>YHWH's provision promise: 'You shall drink from the brook, and I have commanded the ravens to feed you there.' The double provision of water (from Cherith) and food (from ravens) addresses both survival needs. The narrative will show the water source fail first (v7) before the food source is shifted to the Zarephath widow — the provision adapts to the circumstances without interrupting the divine supply.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Elijah's obedience: 'He went and did according to the word of the LORD. He went and lived by the brook Cherith that is east of the Jordan.' The simple obedience formula — 'he went and did according to the word of YHWH' — is the characteristic mark of the faithful prophet in Deuteronomistic narrative. Elijah's going without question or condition establishes his prophetic character from the outset; his faithfulness will be tested later (19:4) but is established first.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The raven provision fulfilled: 'The ravens brought him bread and meat in the morning, and bread and meat in the evening, and he drank from the brook.' The morning-evening feeding pattern echoes the manna provision in the wilderness (Exod 16:12-13: quail in the evening, manna in the morning). Elijah's Cherith episode is a miniature wilderness sojourn: divine provision in a desolate place, preparing the prophet for his mission. The miraculous feed sustains him for the drought's duration at Cherith.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The brook Cherith dried up because there was no rain in the land. The cause of the brook's failure — the very drought Elijah announced — dries up his own provision. The divine provision is not immune to the judgment it announced; Elijah experiences the drought he proclaimed. This provides the narrative occasion for the next stage: the move to Zarephath. The progressive nature of the drought (brook drying up) gives the narrative temporal development.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The word of the LORD came to Elijah again: the repeated prophetic formula signals a new divine directive following the exhaustion of the Cherith provision. The second directive moves the prophet from Israel's territory entirely to Phoenicia — Zarephath belongs to Sidon, Jezebel's homeland. The irony is striking: Elijah is sent to the very country whose Baal-worship Jezebel is importing into Israel, to be fed by a gentile widow.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Elijah came to the gate of the city and behold a widow was there gathering sticks. The gate as the commercial and social hub of ancient cities: the widow gathering sticks at the gate for fuel is in the most public possible location, which makes her accessible. The gate (<em>šaʿar</em>) is also where legal matters were transacted, where the poor came to beg, and where commerce was conducted — the widow at the gate is in the expected place of the destitute seeking help.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Elijah's first request: water. 'Please bring me a little water in a vessel, that I may drink.' The initial request for water — the most basic provision — is followed immediately by the second request for bread while she is already going (v12). The doubling of requests escalates the demand: water first, then food, from a widow who has 'nothing' (v12). The social position of the widow in the ancient Near East: without a husband or adult son, she had no male protector, no claim on common resources, and was dependent on charity.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The widow's response establishes her desperate condition: 'As YHWH your God lives, I have nothing baked, only a handful of flour in a jar and a little oil in a jug.' The oath by YHWH — the Israelite deity — from a Phoenician woman is striking; she may have had contact with Israelite religious culture through trade or travel, or this is the narrative's way of identifying her as a God-fearer. The specific provisions named — <em>kad qāmāḥ</em> (jar of flour) and <em>ṣappaḥat šemen</em> (cruse of oil) — give the account precise detail of subsistence-level food supply.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Elijah's counter-instruction: 'Do not fear. Go and do as you have said, but first make me a small cake from it and bring it to me, and afterward make something for yourself and your son.' The 'do not fear' (<em>ʾal-tîrᵉʾî</em>) formula typically introduces a divine reassurance; here it comes from the prophet. The instruction to feed the prophet first — before the widow feeds herself and her son — is the test of faith that precedes the miracle. The pattern: obedience before provision, not provision as reward for prior faith.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The miracle promise: 'For thus says YHWH the God of Israel: The jar of flour shall not be spent, and the jug of oil shall not be empty, until the day that YHWH sends rain upon the earth.' The specific miracle — inexhaustible small provisions — rather than a dramatic one-time provision, sustains through the duration of the drought. The formula 'YHWH the God of Israel' on a prophet's lips in Phoenicia is the signature of the mission to demonstrate YHWH's sovereignty over Baal's own territory.</p>",
    "15": "<p>She went and did as Elijah said — the obedience formula applied to the widow. The extended provision: 'She and he and her household ate for many days.' The widow's obedience in giving the prophet first brings the extended provision. The household (<em>hû wayhî wᵉḇêtāh</em> — he and she and her household) are all sustained. The miracle persists beyond the initial feeding: 'many days' (<em>yāmîm rabbîm</em>) indicates the ongoing duration of the supernatural supply.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The fulfillment confirmation: 'The jar of flour was not spent, neither did the jug of oil become empty, according to the word of YHWH that he spoke by Elijah.' The standard fulfillment formula confirms the prophetic word. The ongoing miracle of inexhaustible provisions has a loose parallel in the Elisha narrative (2 Kgs 4:1-7, the widow's oil that fills vessels). Both accounts emphasize that YHWH's provision through prophetic agents operates without rational explanation — the jar and jug simply do not empty.</p>",
    "17": "<p>After this the son of the woman, the mistress of the house, became sick; his illness was so severe that there was no breath left in him. The death of the widow's son after the miraculous provision is a second crisis: the miracle that sustained life is followed by death. The Hebrew <em>wayyᵉhî ʾaḥᵃrê haddᵉḇārîm hāʾēlleh</em> ('after these things') is a formula for a narrative crisis following a narrative resolution. The child's breath (<em>nᵉšāmāh</em>) ceasing is the standard idiom for death (cf. Gen 2:7 where YHWH breathes <em>nišmat ḥayyîm</em> into the man).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The widow's accusation: 'What have you against me, O man of God? You have come to me to bring my sin to remembrance and to cause the death of my son!' The theology of the accusation: in the ancient Near East, proximity to a holy person could bring divine punishment for previously unaddressed sins. The widow interprets her son's death as divine punishment for sin (<em>ʿāwôn</em>) that Elijah's presence has 'brought to remembrance' before God. The accusation is not directed at Elijah personally but at the God whose presence Elijah represents.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Elijah's response: 'Give me your son.' He takes the child from her bosom and carries him to the upper room where he lodged and lays him on his own bed. The upper room (<em>ʿăliyyāh</em>) was a guest room or private space above the main living area in ancient Israelite houses — the same term for the room where Elisha will raise the Shunammite woman's son (2 Kgs 4:10-11, 21). The prophet takes the child into his private space for the healing — away from public view, in the intimate sphere where divine action can occur without audience.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Elijah's prayer of lament: 'O YHWH my God, have you brought calamity even upon the widow with whom I sojourn, by killing her son?' The prophet's prayer of lament directed at God — the Psalmic tradition of the lament prayer that accuses God of wrongdoing (<em>hăgam ʿal-hāʾalmānāh</em>, also upon the widow?) — is the model of prophetic intercession. Moses similarly accused God after the golden calf (Exod 32:11-13); the prophets' ability to address God's apparent injustice reflects the intimacy of covenant relationship.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Elijah stretched himself on the child three times and cried to YHWH. The physical contact — stretching (<em>wạyyitmōḏaḏ</em>) the prophet's body on the child — is a gesture whose purpose is uncertain: symbolic identification of the living with the dead, or physical warming (proposed by rationalistic interpreters), or simply the physical gesture accompanying the prayer. Three repetitions establish the completeness of the act. A parallel in 2 Kgs 4:34-35 has Elisha performing a similar stretching-action over the Shunammite's son.</p>",
    "22": "<p>YHWH heard the voice of Elijah and the soul of the child came into him again, and he revived. The resurrection formula: <em>wayyāšāḇ nepeš hayyeledd ʿal-qirbo</em>, the <em>nepeš</em> (life-breath, soul) of the child returned into him. The <em>nepeš</em> as the living principle that departs at death and can be restored by divine action is the OT's understanding of the human person as an animated body — the <em>nepeš</em> is not immortal by nature but given and sustained by YHWH. The restoration of the <em>nepeš</em> is a reversal of the death-process initiated in v17.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Elijah took the child and brought him down from the upper room into the house and gave him to his mother. The physical restoration — bringing the child from the prophet's private space back into the household — is the completion of the miracle. The child is returned to the mother as the intended recipient of the miracle. The movement from the upper room (space of death and prophetic action) to the house (space of family and ordinary life) is the spatial enactment of the child's restoration.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The widow's confession: 'Now I know that you are a man of God and that the word of YHWH in your mouth is truth.' The resurrection miracle produces the theological confession. The designation <em>ʾîš hāʾelōhîm</em> (man of God) is confirmed by the resurrection; the truth (<em>ʾemet</em>) of YHWH's word through his prophet is established by the act. The trajectory: drought announcement (v1), miraculous provision (vv14-16), resurrection (vv17-23), confession (v24). The Elijah cycle establishes the prophet's credentials through progressive demonstrations of YHWH's power through him.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '1kings')
    merge_comm(existing, KINGS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1kings', existing)
    for ch in ['15', '16', '17']:
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(existing.get(ch, {}))} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
